{"questionId":"29618859","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></math>. The graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> has an axis of symmetry at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>The two roots of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℚ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>+</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://